AD  - Centre for Earth Observation Science Department of Geography, University of Manitoba, Winnipeg, MB, R3T 2N2, Canada
AB  - Debris flows are rapid movements of water, rock debris and vegetation down confined channels. Based on field examinations of these channels, a review of historical data and eyewitness accounts of the processes, it is evident that debris flows pose a significant risk to roads, structures and the increasing number of visitors entering Banff National Park. In order to help the Park identify potentially hazardous areas, a GIS database of the locations and attributes of these channels has been developed along with a recurrence interval model. The model assigns hazard ratings to sites, which may become unstable given predetermined short-term atmospheric conditions. Measurements from digitized aerial photographs were evaluated and employed in a recurrence interval model. Photo interpretation experience was important in reducing variance in measurements made. Rates of rock erosion for this type of environment were found to play a key role in the model. There is a predicted 30% decrease in the number of years between successive debris flow events of a given magnitude when the erosion rate is varied between 0.0005 and 0.0007 m/year. Recurrence intervals in this area range from less than 20 to more than 200 years and generally decrease with increasing basin size. Fourteen of the 22 sites have been identified as Increasing or High Hazard based on the recurrence model. The recurrence interval model coupled with a comprehensive GIS database and map provides a mitigative tool that may be used to reduce hazard effects of the debris flows in Banff National Park. © 1998, Taylor & Francis Group, LLC. All rights reserved.
